In [[Roman mythology]], '''Febris''' ("fever") was the goddess who embodied, but also protected people from [[fever]] and [[malaria]]. Febris had three temples in ancient Rome, of which one was located between the [[Palatine Hill|Palatine]] and [[Velabrum]].<ref>[[Valerius Maximus]], ''[[Factorum ac dictorum memorabilium libri IX|Nine Books of Memorable Deeds and Sayings]]'', 2. 5. 6</ref><ref>[[Cicero]], ''[[De Legibus|On The Laws]], 2. 11''</ref><ref>[[Cicero]], ''[[De Natura Deorum|On The Nature of Gods]]'', 3. 25</ref><ref>[[Claudius Aelianus]], ''[http://penelope.uchicago.edu/aelian/ Various History]'', 12. 11</ref> She may have originated from the Roman god [[Februus]]. Among her characteristic attributes are "shrewdness" and "honesty", according to [[Seneca the Younger]]'s ''[[Apocolocyntosis]]''.<ref>Seneca the Younger, ''Apocolocyntosis'', 6</ref>
